Elon Musk and Apple CEO Tim Cook are set to join former President Donald Trump on a diplomatic visit to China later this month, in what analysts describe as an unprecedented blend of business diplomacy and geopolitical manoeuvring.
The delegation, which also includes several other senior US business leaders, is intended to restart trade negotiations between the world&rsquo;s two largest economies. Relations between Washington and Beijing have been strained in recent months following a new round of tariff escalations and technology export restrictions.
Trump confirmed the trip during a press conference at Mar-a-Lago, calling it &ldquo;the deal of the century in the making.&rdquo; Musk and Cook, he said, would help &ldquo;show China what American innovation looks like.&rdquo;
The inclusion of two of America&rsquo;s most prominent tech CEOs is seen as a strategic move. Both Musk and Cook have significant business interests in China — Tesla operates a massive factory in Shanghai, and Apple generates approximately 20% of its revenue from the Chinese market. Their presence signals to Beijing that the US business community is invested in maintaining strong economic ties.
However, the trip has drawn criticism from some lawmakers who argue that it risks legitimizing China&rsquo;s human rights record and trade practices. Senator Marco Rubio called the visit &ldquo;a photo op for an authoritarian regime.&rdquo;
Despite the controversy, financial markets have responded positively to the news, with both Tesla and Apple shares rising on hopes of a trade breakthrough. Analysts caution, however, that the trip&rsquo;s outcomes remain uncertain, and that structural tensions between the two countries are unlikely to be resolved in a single visit.

Prime Minister Keir Starmer confirmed on Tuesday that the UK government will move forward with plans to nationalise British Steel, a decision that marks one of the most significant state interventions in British industry in decades.
Speaking at a press conference in Westminster, Starmer argued that government ownership is necessary to secure the future of the struggling steelmaker, which employs thousands of workers across the UK. &ldquo;British Steel is a strategic national asset. Allowing it to collapse or fall into foreign hands without safeguards would be a failure of leadership,&rdquo; he said.
The announcement comes after months of uncertainty over the company&rsquo;s financial viability. British Steel has faced mounting pressures from high energy costs, aging infrastructure, and global market oversupply, particularly from China. The government has already provided multiple bailout packages to keep the company operational.
Critics, including opposition Conservative MPs and some business groups, have warned that nationalisation will burden taxpayers and stifle private investment. Shadow Business Secretary Claire Coutinho called the plan &ldquo;a reckless leap backwards&rdquo; that would &ldquo;undo decades of market reform.&rdquo;
However, unions broadly welcomed the move. Community Union general secretary Roy Rickhuss said: &ldquo;This is a landmark moment. Workers at British Steel have been living under a cloud of uncertainty for too long. Public ownership offers a path to sustainable investment and job security.&rdquo;
The government has not yet disclosed the full cost of the nationalisation or the compensation terms for current owners. A detailed white paper is expected within the next 30 days, outlining the transition timeline and governance structure of the newly nationalised entity.
